<TITLE> HuJI leader sent to jail </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, May 02 (bdnews24.com) A member of banned Islamist outfit Harkat-ul-Jihad-al-Islami (HuJI) was sent to jail on Sunday. Dhaka's Chief Metropolitan Magistrate Ismail Hossain ordered Golam Mostafa to jail after having spent eight days in remand in two phases in an anti-terrorism case. DB inspector Fazlul Haque applied for Mostafa to be sent to jail. On Apr 27, the police were given four days to question Mostafa. Mostafa had earlier been remanded in police custody for four days on Apr 17. The HuJI man was arrested on Apr 16 this year on charges of trying to organise and strengthen the banned outfit secretly. This is the second time he had been attested The alleged militant was first arrested on Dec 2, 2007 from a house in the capital's Bashundhara residential area, which is also Dhaka's diplomatic zone. Then a British passport, a pistol and five jihadist books were also recovered from his possession. Mostafa was sentenced to 17 years in prison but managed to get bail from the High Court. Police had said that Mostafa started organising HuJI and became involved in different criminal acts after he got out of jail. bdnews24.
